         <div>
            <head>2.3.1884 Sonntag</head>
            <p>
               <placeName type="write" key="49069">Hamburg</placeName>. March 2. 1884. Sunday.</p>
            <p> Robert<note type="reg">
                  <persName key="1156">Blümer</persName>
               </note> has got a
               pleurésie and is very ill. I stopped at home the whole day. In the evening I went to
               Schwere&#x2019;s and had tea there. Before tea Gustav<note type="reg">
                  <persName key="1247">Schwere</persName>
               </note>, Martin<note type="reg">
                  <persName key="1157">Blümer</persName>
               </note> and I played
               66. I was very unlucky. After tea <persName key="1247">Gustav</persName> and
                  <persName key="1249">Susanne Schwere</persName> played a sonate of <persName key="8636">Beethoven</persName>. I worked a great deal at my piece today, which I
               mean to be a kind of prayer. At the end of the first verse a choir of priests is
               supposed to be singing the requiem. I have just begun this latter part. I was rather
               puzzled how to tack it on to the first part; but now I think I will not make any
               transition and let the second part come in on itself, which is certainly the most
               natural. There is a long article about <persName key="7392">Mackays</persName> in the paper
               today. Their law suit with <persName key="1250">Meissonnier</persName> seems to be
               making great noise. <persName key="103">Mamma</persName> writes that her picture<note type="reg">
                  <name type="work" key="35953">Portrait von Alice Kessler</name>
               </note> by <persName key="1251">Kirchbach</persName> is
               getting something awful although se sits 3 hours every day.</p>
